<br>
FnF<br>
Reso<br>
AS<br>
DS<br>
<br>
Lets look at these four choices first.  <br>
<br>
Fire and Fury, Resolution, and SA (the old Awakened Souls) are what most people with experience on FV would consider the &quot;Big Three&quot; Guilds in terms of Powergamer/ Raiding Guilds.  They all say they raid five days a week, and by and large this is relatively true, so to join any of them, one must be willing to sacrafice a good deal of you free time to raid frequently.<br>
<br>
Fire and Fury, the guild many poeple would describe as the premier guild of FV, was the break away guild from the pack on FV early on.  FnF produced many of the server firsts on FV, and did this with smaller numbers then other guilds; A philosphy that might be described as doing more with less.  In general, FnF members were better equipped, and were higher level during this time.  A reflection of this philosphy is their demanding application requirements, which are the strictest on the server.  While this insures a high quality of membership, based on what they find important in an applicant, it will keep many more casual players from applying to them.  FnF has about 40 members, with about 20 to 30 showing up at any particular raid, along with 5 applicants or guests.  Membership of FnF has sufferend in the past three months or so, with many prominent members leaving or retiring (Gore, Ramel, and Cloude for example).  This has casused their raiding to platue, in which they are no longer breaking new group with the same frequency they did previously.  If you can adhere to a demanding raid schedule, FnF is a possible, and attractive choice.  FnF frequents high end Luclin and Velious zones.  <br>
<br>
Resolution, FnF's traditional rival, has often been characterized by one self evident trait, its sheer size.  Comprised of 77 members, Reso draws from the largest player base of any guild on FV that I'm aware of.  This number however is deceptive, as many members of Resolution play multiple characters.  Martially, Resolution is able to achieve suscess at all the mobs FnF can, and when Resolution is focused, and have more of their members on then off, they become suscessful at mobs that FnF has yet to attempt, like named mobs in NToV.  Resolution is at the top end of Velious ATM, and raid at Velious locations weekly.  Resolution generally starts raids earlier then FnF, perhaps by one to two and a half hours on weekdays.  Resolution also is reaching its cap on certain classes, monk for example which they feel they have an overabundance of.  However, even with a dozen clerics on their roster, they still recruit for them.  If you offer a class they are looking for, and can adhere to a demanding raid schedule, Resolution is another attractive option.  Reso frequents high end Luclin and Velious zones, stressing new mobs in Ssra and NToV.<br>
<br>
Souls Arisen, the remade Awakened Souls, has recently undergone a housecleaning of its leadership.  Often seen as the &quot;bad boy&quot; guild of FV, SA does offer a demanding raid schedule like both Reso and FnF.  I'm told that their recent refit has not deminished their capacity to do mobs, but as I've not raided with them, this is not something I can verify.  SA differs from the other two guilds, in that they allow the active use of more then one character.  How wide spread this practice is I couldn't say, but this could make SA a more attractive choice for multiple account players, who can play two accounts with some effectiveness.  SA is active in high end Velious zones, particularly ST, as well as Luclin.<br>
<br>
Dreadstorm comes in at number four, based on active raiding level.  Dreadstorm can be described as the first of the second generation raiding guilds.  This may sound deragtory, but its not.  Dreadstorm simply doesn't raid with the frequency, and at the strength presented by the previous guilds.  Dreadstorm is like a half dozen guilds (Clan Werre, Ebon Storm, and Tribulation among them) that raid the lower high-end Luclin zones regularly or semi regularly.  Dreadstorm is unique in that they raid during the day (based on PST), because they are a guild comprised largely of Europeians.  This allows them to monopolize certain mobs, becasue they can reach them before other guilds can form up the strength necessary to field a signiciantly strong raid force.  DS raids perhaps twice a week, one of those days being Saturday (their heavy raid day).  For those loosing for a more relaxed raid schedule, DS, and similiar guilds are the better choice.<br>
<br>
There are perhaps a dozen other guilds that raid with some frequency.  The Fellowship is a coalition of &quot;Good&quot; race guilds, and they mount Hate level raids.  There are also the Open Raid Community, but for high raid quality, nothing surpasses a Guild Raid in general level of organization.  I know less about the &quot;Second Generation&quot; Guilds as I describe them, but in general, they are lower level, and as a result target mobs in Hate, Fear, and Sky as opposed to named mobs in Kael, Icewell Keep, and ToV.<br>
<br>
There is my summary of the Guild Options open to people looking for a Raiding Guild Sneez.  <br>
<br>
The only other option is to start a multi-guild raiding association to do the higher level mobs.  High end Velious and Luclin mobs that the &quot;Big Three&quot; tackle regularly aren't out of the question for the rest of us, it will just take someone coming forward to pull it all together.  I did it once, I don't doubt that someone else could pull out the stops to do it again.<br>
<br>
Jabbs/Paprika/Chestnut<br>
